{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Advantages and Disadvantages of Relational Databases (RDBMS) vs NoSQL Databases\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Relational Databases (RDBMS)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Examples: MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, MariaDB, SQL Server\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Advantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab ACID Compliance (Reliability & Integrity)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Ensures Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability, guaranteeing reliable transactions.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Ideal for systems that require data integrity, such as banking, accounting, and ERP.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Structured and Organized Schema\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Data is stored in structured tables with strict schemas.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Reduces redundancy and improves organization through normalization.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Powerful Querying with SQL\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab SQL allows flexible, complex queries, joins, and aggregations.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Universal and standardized language across most RDBMS systems.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Data Integrity and Enforcement of Constraints\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Relationships are enforced using primary keys, foreign keys, and constraints, ensuring consistent data.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Mature Ecosystem & Tools\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Robust tools for security, backup, optimization, and reporting developed over decades.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Disadvantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Limited Scalability\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Typically scales vertically rather than horizontally.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Can lead to cost inefficiencies for high-scale applications.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Schema Rigidity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Schema changes often require migrations or downtime.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Performance Bottlenecks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Complex joins and transactions across large datasets may slow performance.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Not Ideal for Unstructured Data\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Inefficient for storing non-tabular or dynamic data such as multimedia or logs.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 NoSQL Databases\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Examples: MongoDB, Cassandra, DynamoDB, Redis, Neo4j\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Advantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Flexible or Schema-less Design\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Supports dynamic, unstructured, or semi-structured data.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab New fields or data structures can be added without downtime.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Horizontal Scalability\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Built for distributed systems\u8212-scales by adding more nodes.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Ideal for large-scale, high-traffic applications.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab High Performance at Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Optimized for quick reads/writes and data ingestion.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Some systems provide near-real-time performance.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Supports Multiple Data Models\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Includes document, key-value, column-family, and graph models.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Each model suits different use cases.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab High Availability and Fault Tolerance\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Data replication across multiple servers ensures uptime and reliability.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Disadvantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Weaker Consistency Guarantees\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Prioritizes availability and performance over strict consistency (CAP theorem).\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Often leads to eventual consistency.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Lack of Standard Query Language\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Each system has its own query syntax, making switching harder.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Limited Transactions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Multi-record or multi-collection transactions may be unsupported or complex.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Younger Technology Stack\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Less mature ecosystems and tool support compared to RDBMS.\sa180\sa180\par}
